\begin_layout Section

\size largest
Brownian Motion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition

\size largest
Fix 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 and define 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p\left(t,x,y\right)=\frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi t}}e^{-\frac{\left(x-y\right)^{2}}{2t}}
\]

\end_inset

for 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 Then for 
\begin_inset Formula $0<t_{1}<t_{2}<\cdots<t_{n}$
\end_inset

 define a measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{t_{1},\dots,t_{k}}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{k}$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\mu_{t_{1},\dots,t_{k}}\left(F_{1}\times\cdots\times F_{k}\right) & = & \int_{F_{1}}\cdots\int_{F_{k}}p\left(t_{1},x,x_{1}\right)p\left(t_{2}-t_{1},x_{1},x_{2}\right)\cdots\\
 &  & p\left(t_{k}-t_{k-1},x_{k-1},x_{k}\right)dx_{1}dx_{2}\cdots dx_{k}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

for 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{i}\subset\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 with the convention that 
\begin_inset Formula $p\left(0,x,y\right)dx=\delta_{x}\left(y\right)$
\end_inset

 a unit point mass at 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 Extend to all finite sequences 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{1},\dots,t_{n}$
\end_inset

 and since 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{F_{i}}p\left(t,x,y\right)dx=1$
\end_inset

 Kolmogorov's Extension theorem says there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\Omega,\mathcal{F},P^{x}\right)$
\end_inset

 and a stochastic process 
\begin_inset Formula $B=\left\{ B_{t}\right\} _{t\geq0}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 such that the finite-dimensional distributions of 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{t}$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
P^{x}\left(B_{t_{1}}\in F_{1}\times\cdots\times B_{t_{k}}\in F_{k}\right) & = & \int_{F_{1}}\cdots\int_{F_{k}}p\left(t_{1},x,x_{1}\right)p\left(t_{2}-t_{1},x_{1},x_{2}\right)\cdots\label{eq:brownianmotiondef}\\
 &  & p\left(t_{k}-t_{k-1},x_{k-1},x_{k}\right)dx_{1}dx_{2}\cdots dx_{k}\nonumber 
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

Such a process
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\size largest
One that has these finite-dimensional distributions.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is called a Brownian motion.
 The paths of a Brownian motion happen to be almost surely continuous
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\size largest
Wiener's theorem.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (but nowhere differentiable!) so with each 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\in\Omega$
\end_inset

 you can identify a continuous function 
\begin_inset Formula $t\rightarrow B_{t}\left(\omega\right)$
\end_inset

 from 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[0,\infty\right)$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus a perspective on Brownian motion is that it's the space of continuous
 functions 
\begin_inset Formula $C\left(\left[0,\infty\right),\mathbb{R}\right)$
\end_inset

 equipped with the measures 
\begin_inset Formula $P^{x}$
\end_inset

 above
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\size largest
Which as discussed are product measures on a function space.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

