Let's construct a severely simplified model.
 Suppose the stock moves in discrete increments per discrete steps.
 For example suppose the current stock price is $20 and in a quarter it
 will be either $22 or $18.
 Let's value a $21 European call option.
 If the stock rises to 22$ then the value of the option is $1 (to whomever
 bought it, since they get to purchase the $22 stock at $21) but if the
 stock goes down to 20 then the value of the option is $0 (to whomever bought
 it since they wouldn't exercise the contract).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size largest
We assume that zero arbitrage opportunities exist in the market (implied
 by efficient market hypothesis) and construct a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
