riskless
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 portfolio.
 Because of zero arbitrage opportunities this portfolio should earn the
 riskfree rate.
 Let the portfolio be a long position (buy) in 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta$
\end_inset

 shares of the underlying stock and a short position (sell side) in one
 call option.
 Calculate the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta$
\end_inset

 that makes the portfolio riskless.
 If the price of the stock moves from $20 to $22 then the portfolio is worth
 
\begin_inset Formula $22\Delta-1$
\end_inset

 (since we end up having to buy the underlying at $22 and then selling for
 $21).
 If the price of the stock moves down to $18 then the value of the portfolio
 is just 
\begin_inset Formula $18\Delta$
\end_inset

 because the person in the long position of the call option doesn't exercise.
 The portfolio is riskless if the value is the same regardless of whether
 the stock price goes up or down and so 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
22\Delta-1=18\Delta\Rightarrow\Delta=0.25
\]

\end_inset

Thus the portfolio is long .25 shares and short 1 option.
